[recv] {"type": "turn_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Fixing JUnit issues**\n\nI’m noticing we need to address a mismatch error with JUnit; it seems SpringExtension 7 is expecting a JUnit 6 API. Since we have constraints from BOM 5.9, I’m wondering about upgrading directly to JUnit 6.0.0. This upgrade could include the necessary platform and vintage engine. I’m trying to determine whether I should use 6.0.0 or 6.0.3, given our local cache. Finally, I’m contemplating how our class templates are being invoked within JUnit and if adjustments are needed.\n\n**Adjusting build.gradle settings**\n\nI realize the scanner needs to identify the top-level annotated ClassTemplate and ExtendWith Spring for JUnit to execute correctly. However, there might be issues with classpath scanning. I’m thinking about editing the build.gradle file, and should I set the version to either 6.0.0 or 6.0.3? Since it's 2026, 6.0.0 seems safer to ensure compatibility with Spring 7.0.0. I’m also considering whether to define a separate static fixture class to avoid using SpringExtension directly in the top-level class. It feels like a better approach!\n\n**Considering JUnit 5.13 behavior**\n\nI’m thinking about how MergedAnnotations getClassArray might load the class but not link the methods. With JUnit 5.13, it can discover the @ClassTemplate annotation. But if it's scanning and discovers a disabled fixture, I wonder if JUnit 5.13 will load SpringExtension and possibly call supports. It’s a bit of a technical puzzle, and I'm trying to piece together how it all interacts.\n\n**Editing code structure**\n\nI'm thinking about how to edit the code. First, I want to ensure the top-level class is properly annotated. I'll consider removing unnecessary imports, but I still need ClassTemplate and ExtendWith for the fixture. Don't forget to add the Disabled import! It might make sense to add the fixture before the provider as well, so I'll plan to do on